North Korea says there's "no way" to disarm one-sided, trustless
North Korea's Foreign Minister told the UN Saturday that continuing sanctions deepened distrust of the United States and there is no way the country would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
At the annual general meeting of the world organization, Ri Yong-hou said that "significant measures of goodwill have been taken in the past year", for example, we stop nuclear and missile tests, destruction of the nuclear test site and promises not to distribute nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
"Without having confidence in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security and under no circumstances will we first disarm one-sided."
While Ri expressed North Korea's known complaints about Washington's resistance against a "staged" approach to eliminate nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it had taken gradual measures, his statement seemed significant as it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement from Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the President of the United States and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work for "nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula", and Trump gave security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950–1953 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang should first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also opposed calls to ease the strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists "first to remove nuclear weapons" and increase pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and even object to the "declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a meaningless dream of those who do not know us.
The problem, however, is that continuing sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting was planned between Kim and Trump, for which the U.S. leader stressed through the UN earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister emphasized on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-In over the past five months and added: "If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the removal of nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula would not have reached such a standstill.
However, Ri's tone of speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korean missiles to the mainland of the United States was inevitable after "the evil president" Trump called Kim "a man-rocket" on a suicide mission.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with "total destruction", praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said that much still remains to be done and sanctions must remain in force while North Korea removes nuclear weapons.
Wednesday, Trump stressed that there was no deadline for this and said, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must necessarily continue until full, final and confirmed nuclear disarmament is implemented."
The Security Council unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stop funding Pyongyang's nuclear program and ballistic missile program.
Pompeo met Ri at the UN General Assembly's colloari and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
This year Pompeo visited North Korea three times, but his last trip on went well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but just a few hours later North Korea accused him of making "gangster demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to destroy a missile site and nuclear complex if the United States took "the appropriate measures".
According to him, Kim told him that "the corresponding measures" he sought were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and that he wanted to achieve normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students on a class for enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year led all students to sleep more in an effort to fight the growing culture of learning "all night" using caffeine.
A teacher found that students at number one university in the world often don't even consider when it comes to the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keysler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical Faculty and a specialist at the Brigham Hospital and the Women's Hospital, prepared the course he thought was the first of his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"A girl came to me at the end and said, "Why are they only telling me this now, in my senior year?"
She said that no one has ever talked to her about the importance of the dream that surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being held for the first time this year, explains to students the most important thing about how good sleeping habits help academic and sporting achievements, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Bareira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical Faculty and executive director of the university's health services, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were suffering from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
One-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is an image of a room in a dorm where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to explain to them the effects of caffeine and light, how sports achievements are influenced by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of the routine of bedtime.
Another part of the participants relates how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the health effects of the choice to smoke," Professor Kaisler added.
The pride culture of "all night learning" still exists, he says and added that modern technology and constantly increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring sufficient and quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students in the fight against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he says – even in order to avoid getting fat, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Keysler prepare the course by taking one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He says his course "opened his eyes" and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete such a curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Kaisler recommends that students think about setting a bedtime and wake-up alarm and knowing the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
