The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats.
A new study carried out in a mansion in the Scottish mountains aims to establish how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hopes are that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help lead future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats as well as brown straddle water nightdresses in Inverewe Gardens at Western Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations on the estate to track bat activities during the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using hand detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's call sounds, as well as which species produce them.
A map of habitat and a report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by any species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and in Britain have generally decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by the construction activities that affect their refuges and lead to habitat loss.
Risk to populations may be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical handling of building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In fact bats are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use advanced echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts conducting regular surveys, inspections of shelters and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even created the first in Scotland and the only special bat reserve in the Treave Manor in the Dumfreece and Galloway district, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
The estate manager David Thompson says it's perfect territory for them.
"Here, in Treave, we have a great pitch for bats," he noted.
"We have old buildings, many adult trees and a suitable habitat completed.
But there are many other things about bats that are not known, so the work we do here and in other estates will help us better understand what they need to flourish."
He emphasises that it is important to check for the presence of bats before property maintenance activities are carried out, as it is possible that involuntary destruction of an asylum will kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Farrell, Scottish employee at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged society to help.
She said, "I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, as we simply do not know what happens to their populations."
