Here are some basic facts about Palu and Dongala, which are located on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the province of central Sulawesi, located at the end of a narrow beach strip on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with a population of 379 800 in 2017.
The town celebrated its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami struck it.
Dongala is a regent that extends more than 300 km (180 miles) along the coastline of Sulawesi Island.
The regency, which an administrative region smaller than a province, had an estimated population of 299200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the foundations of the economy of the province of central Sulawesi, especially in the coastal region of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also important for the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morovali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Dongala have been hit several times by a tsunami in the past 100 years, according to Indonesian disaster recovery agency data.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongala.
Tsunami struck the western part of Dongala and in 1996, when nine people died.
Indonesia is located on the seismic "Pacific Fire Ring" and is regularly decimated by earthquakes.
Here are some of the great earthquakes and tsunami waves in recent years:
2004: A strong quake on December 26 on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in North Sumatra activated a tsunami wave that struck 14 countries and killed 226,000 people across the coast of the Indian Ocean, with more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 quake decimated Indonesia's most populated island, Java, activating a tsunami that crashed in the south coast, destroying nearly 700 people.
2009: A magnitude 7.6 earthquake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 earthquake hit one of the Mentawai Islands and activated a 10-metre tsunami wave that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake hit Pidi Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastation of the deadly earthquake and tsunami in 2004.
This time, no tsunami was activated, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Strong quakes decimated the tourist island of Lombock in Indonesia, killed more than 500 people, most of whom on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily at a standstill.
