The last time a death sentence was executed in New York City in a federal case was in 1953 – Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple who were executed after a conspiracy conviction and espionage for the Soviet Union in the Cold War, two years earlier.
Both Rosenberg were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, an Uzbek national, showed no sense of remorse during the days and months after the attack, according to the court documents.
