New for the Red Tide: Concentrations decrease in Pinelas, Manotti and Sarasota
Florida's latest report of the Committee for Fish and Wildlife shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions for breaking growth in Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier regions – this shows a decrease in concentrations.
Water sections with an excessive red tide bloom spread approximately 130 miles along the coast, from northern Pinelas County to southern Lee County.
Algae sections can be seen 10 miles off the Hillsboro County coast, but they are less than last week.
A red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
During the past week, there were reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal area or slightly further inland in Pinelas County, low to high concentrations along the Hillsboro Coast, prerequisites for high concentrations in Manotey County, prerequisites for high concentrations in the coast or further inland in Sarasota County, prerequisites for moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, prerequisites for high concentrations in the coast or further within Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Reports continue to be received of respiratory tract inflammation in Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there were no reports of respiratory tract inflammation in North West Florida.
